  <h3 class="mt2">2 · State Vector vs. Shot-Based Simulation</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
    <thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>State Vector Simulator</th><th>Shot-Based Simulator</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td class="tk">Output</td><td class="tv">Exact complex amplitudes aₓ</td><td class="tv">Sampled counts per basis state</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tk">Phase access</td><td><span class="badge green">✓ Yes</span></td><td><span class="badge red">✗ No</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tk">Statistical noise</td><td><span class="badge green">✗ None (exact)</span></td><td><span class="badge gold">✓ Yes — improves with shots</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tk">Use case</td><td class="tv">Debug, verify algorithm correctness</td><td class="tv">Hardware-like measurement workflows</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tk">Convergence</td><td class="tv">Exact always</td><td class="tv">Converges to exact as shots → ∞ (Born Rule)</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tk">AWS SV1</td><td class="tv">Up to 24 qubits</td><td class="tv">TN1 (Tensor Network): up to 50+ qubits</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table></div>

  <h3 class="mt2">3 · Three Noise Types to Know</h3>
  <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
    <thead><tr><th>Noise Type</th><th>Physical Cause</th><th>Qiskit Aer Model</th><th>Effect on Bell State</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td class="tk">Depolarizing</td><td class="tv">Gate imperfection — applies wrong operation with prob p</td><td><code>depolarizing_error(p, n)</code></td><td class="tv">Output distribution spreads — skewed from 50/50</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tk">Amplitude damping</td><td class="tv">Energy relaxation — |1⟩ decays to |0⟩ (T₁ decay)</td><td><code>amplitude_damping_error(gamma)</code></td><td class="tv">Biases measurements toward |0⟩</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tk">Readout error</td><td class="tv">Measurement misassignment — 0↔1 flip</td><td><code>ReadoutError([[1-p, p],[p, 1-p]])</code></td><td class="tv">Counts appear in wrong bitstrings</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table></div>

  <h3 class="mt2">4 · Quantifying Noise — Fidelity &amp; Leakage</h3>
  <div class="g2">
    <div class="panel cyan">
      <div style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.68rem;color:var(--cyan);margin-bottom:.4rem">STATE FIDELITY</div>
      <p style="font-size:.83rem;margin-bottom:.4rem"><code>F = ⟨Φ+|ρ_noisy|Φ+⟩</code></p>
      <p style="font-size:.83rem;color:var(--text2);margin:0">F=1 → perfect. F↓ as noise increases. F&gt;0.5 certifies genuine entanglement (cannot be explained classically).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="panel violet">
      <div style="font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.68rem;color:var(--violet2);margin-bottom:.4rem">MEASUREMENT LEAKAGE</div>
      <p style="font-size:.83rem;margin-bottom:.4rem"><code>L = P(|01⟩) + P(|10⟩)</code></p>
      <p style="font-size:.83rem;color:var(--text2);margin:0">Probability of undesired outcomes. L=0 → perfect. L↑ as noise increases. Complementary to fidelity: F↓ implies L↑.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3 class="mt2">5 · Simulator vs. Real QPU — When to Use What</h3>
